          "text": "Good. Both paths it is. Now let me propose approaches.\n\n## Approaches\n\n### Option A: Quarantine table (recommended)\n\nAdd a `quarantined_messages` table. When deserialization fails, move the row there with the error reason and timestamp. Quarantined rows are:\n- Excluded from normal fetch operations\n- Visible via a `stats()` extension or dedicated admin query\n- Cleaned up by the existing TTL cleanup task (same `expires_at` as the original row)\n\n**Pros:** Full audit trail. Recoverable if a future code version can deserialize the data (e.g., format migration bug). Operators can inspect quarantined data.\n**Cons:** Schema migration (v1→v2). Slightly more storage.\n\n### Option B: Soft-delete flag on existing table\n\nAdd a `quarantined_at` column to `mailbox_messages`. Corrupt rows get flagged instead of deleted. All existing queries add `AND quarantined_at IS NULL`.\n\n**Pros:** No second table, simpler queries.\n**Cons:** Every query must remember the filter. Easy to miss one. Pollutes the main table with corrupt data that indexes must skip.\n\n### Option C: Separate quarantine table with raw blob preservation\n\nSame as Option A, but instead of moving the full row, store only `(id, routing_key, message_id, raw_blob, error, quarantined_at, original_expires_at)` — preserving the exact bytes that failed to parse.\n\n**Pros:** Maximum forensic value — you can re-attempt deserialization on the original bytes.\n**Cons:** Slightly more complex than A, but the data is already available.\n\n**My recommendation: Option C.** The whole point of quarantine over deletion is recoverability. Storing the raw blob that failed deserialization is the key value — without it, quarantine is just delayed deletion. The implementation cost over A is negligible (we already have the raw bytes in hand when the error occurs).",
